{"cursor":"23648","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n in 2005. In Tibet, nomads constitute about 40% of ethnic Tibetan population. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/picture_gallery/06/asia_pac_tibetan_-\n nomads/html/1.stm In pictures: Tibetan nomads] BBC News ]] nomads from\n Northeast Africa.]]\n\nA 'nomad' (, nomas, plural Î½Î¿Î¼Î¬Î´ÎµÏ, nomades; meaning one roaming about for\npasture, pastoral tribe), commonly known as an 'itinerant' in modern-day\ncontexts, is a member of a community of people who move from one place to\nanother, rather than settling permanently in one location. There are an\nestimated 30â40 million nomads in the world.\n\nMany cultures have traditionally been nomadic, but traditional nomadic behavior\nis increasingly rare in industrialized countries. Nomadic cultures are discussed\nin three categories according to economic specialization: hunter-gatherers,\npastoral nomads, and \"peripatetic nomads\".\n\nNomadic hunting and gathering, following seasonally available wild plants and\ngame, is by far the oldest human subsistence method. Pastoralists raise herds,\ndriving them or moving with them, in patterns that normally avoid depleting\npastures beyond their ability to recover. Peripatetic nomads, who offer the\nskills of a craft or trade to those with whom they travel, are most common in\nindustrialized nations.\n","linknr":470,"url":"Itinerant","recorded":1362562717,"links":90,"instances":["people","food"],"pdf":["http://jwsr.ucr.edu/archive/vol8/number3/pdf/jwsr-v8n3-kradin.pdf"],"categories":["Nomads|*","Itinerant living|","Cultural anthropology","Simple living","Demography"],"headings":["Common characteristics","Hunter-gatherers","Pastoralism","Contemporary peripatetic minorities in Europe and Asia{{anchor|Peripatetic minorities}}","Gallery","See also","References","Further reading"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia